THE bug is the data race on the shared accumulator `total`: `total += v * v` is executed concurrently by up to 4 goroutines with no synchronization, so concurrent read-modify-writes lose updates and the sum comes out too small (verified with `go run -race`). The loop variable capture of `v` is NOT a bug under `go 1.24` (per-iteration loop variables since Go 1.22). Correct fix: protect the accumulation, e.g. guard `total += v * v` with a `sync.Mutex` (Lock/Unlock around it), or use `atomic.AddInt64`/per-goroutine partial sums combined after `wg.Wait()`. Example fix preserving the design:
```go
func SumSquares(in []int) int {
	total := 0
	var mu sync.Mutex
	var wg sync.WaitGroup
	sem := make(chan struct{}, 4)
	for _, v := range in {
		wg.Add(1)
		sem <- struct{}{}
		go func() {
			defer wg.Done()
			defer func() { <-sem }()
			mu.Lock()
			total += v * v
			mu.Unlock()
		}()
	}
	wg.Wait()
	return total
}
```

