This Go cache occasionally hangs forever in production under load, but it never hangs in my unit tests (which are single-threaded). The Go race detector reports nothing. Identify the bug, explain the EXACT interleaving of goroutines that triggers the hang, and give a minimal correct fix. Don't just paper over it.

```go
package main

import (
	"sync"
)

type Cache struct {
	mu   sync.RWMutex
	data map[string]int
}

func NewCache() *Cache {
	return &Cache{data: map[string]int{}}
}

// GetOrTotal returns data[k] if present, otherwise the sum of all values.
func (c *Cache) GetOrTotal(k string) int {
	c.mu.RLock()
	defer c.mu.RUnlock()
	if v, ok := c.data[k]; ok {
		return v
	}
	return c.Sum()
}

// Sum returns the total of all values.
func (c *Cache) Sum() int {
	c.mu.RLock()
	defer c.mu.RUnlock()
	s := 0
	for _, v := range c.data {
		s += v
	}
	return s
}

func (c *Cache) Set(k string, v int) {
	c.mu.Lock()
	defer c.mu.Unlock()
	c.data[k] = v
}
```

Many concurrent goroutines call GetOrTotal, Sum, and Set on the same *Cache. What is the bug, what interleaving causes the hang, and how do you fix it correctly?

gold:
Bug: recursive read-locking of the same sync.RWMutex. GetOrTotal does c.mu.RLock() and, on a cache miss, calls c.Sum() which does c.mu.RLock() again. Go's sync.RWMutex is write-preferring and explicitly NOT reentrant (its doc forbids recursive read locking precisely because of this). Triggering interleaving: (1) Goroutine A calls GetOrTotal(missing key) and acquires the outer RLock. (2) Goroutine B calls Set(...) and calls c.mu.Lock(); since A holds a read lock, B blocks and is now QUEUED as a pending writer. (3) A (cache miss) calls Sum() -> c.mu.RLock(); because a writer (B) is waiting, the write-preferring RWMutex refuses to grant the new read lock, so A blocks. Now A waits for the inner RLock that B is blocking, and B waits for A to release the outer RLock -> classic deadlock. It needs concurrency (a writer must arrive between A's two RLocks), which is why single-threaded tests and the race detector never see it. Correct fix: do not re-lock. Extract the locked body of Sum into an unexported helper that assumes the lock is already held, and call that from inside GetOrTotal:

func (c *Cache) sumLocked() int { s := 0; for _, v := range c.data { s += v }; return s }
func (c *Cache) GetOrTotal(k string) int { c.mu.RLock(); defer c.mu.RUnlock(); if v, ok := c.data[k]; ok { return v }; return c.sumLocked() }
func (c *Cache) Sum() int { c.mu.RLock(); defer c.mu.RUnlock(); return c.sumLocked() }

(Switching RWMutex to sync.Mutex is NOT a fix — Mutex is also non-reentrant, so GetOrTotal calling Sum would self-deadlock immediately, even with no writer. Dropping and re-acquiring the lock between the map check and Sum introduces a TOCTOU race and is also wrong.)

